r business. You need software to:</p><ul> <li>Plan tasks</li><li>Review resource capacity</li><li>Assign resources</li><li>Capture time against tasks to compare estimates versus actuals</li><li>Communicate with customers on a routine basis, easily and effectively</li><li>Capture issues, risks, scope changes, and communications from clients</li><li>Keep your team and clients on-schedule with good reporting and dashboards</li></ul> <p><em>TeamHeadquarters provides you with the means to execute your implementation projects with maximum efficiency, effectiveness, and precision. The resulting increase in capacity translates directly to the bottom line.</em></p></div><div class="media panel"> <h4 class="media-heading">2. Supporting Clients</h4> <i class="fa fa-headphones pull-right" style="color: rgb(43, 73, 161); font-size: 6em; text-align: right; border: 6px solid rgb(43, 73, 161); padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px;"></i> <p>The lines get blurred pretty quick when the same team that is working on projects is supporting clients. Without a unified support system, you're battling your own processes. Integrating Customer Care with Project work is going to give a comprehensive picture of past, present and future workloads. You need a system that will:</p><ul> <li>Process inbound customer support requests</li><li>Allow the team to capture time on support</li><li>Assign customer requests to individuals on the team and onto projects</li><li>Keep customer fully in the loop</li><li>Provide a unified view of all customer work across support and projects</li></ul> <p><em>TeamHeadquarters improves service by connecting your project tasks and services tickets in a single unified system. Implementing TeamHeaduarters will give your team the tools they need to service customers and execute projects and give management the information they need to schedule and manage capacity.</em></p></div><div class="media panel"> <h4 class="media-heading">3. Managing Routine Operations</h4> <span clas